The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile providers are among the most expensive in Europe has been reported on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps taken by the European Commission in regulating roaming fees, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile carriers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile phone providers like to shy away from the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Chairman of the Council, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has often stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that a classic provider with its own network doesn’t have very many opportunities (by the way, it would hardly find frequencies either).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market that brought with it a significant price reduction, to which also the classic mobile providers had to respond.
There were similar voices in the UK before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don’t have to look for examples for long.
In February, we reported the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100,000 customers and thus become the country’s fifth largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind mobilization.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual vendors need far less customers than a classic vendor.
They do not require relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less comprehensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good chess move to put on a non-clicky target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose mobile - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the company that operates this virtual provider.
It’s hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could stand in the Czech Republic as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In the Czech Republic chancelos, say mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
“While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
It is more likely that Mobilking will enter the market in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Finance Group, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the current mobile radio providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The GTS Nowera Group has long shown its interest in launching a virtual mobile provider, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we were already able to achieve negotiation progress," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At this point, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specificity compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefónica O2 said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2’s statement: “So far we have not found a viable and beneficial project on both sides on which to build further.”
And she adds: “In the network of T-Mobile, by the end of the year, a virtual provider will hardly appear.
At this point, we should already have a concrete offer to be able to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet.”
Responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
It is easy to understand how mobile providers act, another provider would call it more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor make it easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long way around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>TU websites.
Now, however, U:fon is rightly suited as an argument for why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, in view of this approach of the mobile operator, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is astounded.
This is not just about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which in the Czech Republic unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, relates to this whole problem its typical attitude.
“The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of Foreign Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in his reply to our request.
Such a wording would not be surprising to the representatives of the providers.
This is more than suspicious from an authority that represents the interests of consumers and is intended, inter alia, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, it is likely that pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
It is really shocking that in this case the almost already ringing harmony of the three mobile radio providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is at stake.
Just like the exact same gasoline price at the gas stations, it is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
“The Authority has not discovered any indications in this respect that it is advisable to act against competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers have a dominant market position, so he also does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his trading in the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking by the Telecommunications Regulatory Authority," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, after telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for a virtual provider to enter the market, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And, of course, the mobile carrier has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile phone providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Nowera mentioned above) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The removal of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted Novelle of the Telecommunications Act, the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> has failed to implement the expansion of the competences of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of professionals have promised an improvement of the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one's looking
Firstly, the operation of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unobserved.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
Typically, these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected.
The joke is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile providers prohibit a similar type of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms, which we will then deal with, which can lead to an termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that something like this will not happen to the operators of mobile phones.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not lead to overlooked profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, after all, the services of these companies are used by only a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot fully have it like the normal customers of mobile phone providers."
Alone, however, the <0xC4><0x8C>TU should at least be strange.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Mobile phone providers close their eyes to such a move, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the providers’ statement, they would not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a marked drop in prices for the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of the services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies were taking action at these moments, not in any way trying to protect the interests of the mobile phone providers, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and followed this.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than advantageous.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is true and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon re-emerge.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other stakeholders.
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
