Rats also have feelings.
Does a rat or a snail flee in danger mean that it also feels fear?
The neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how can you check if they feel the same when they behave similarly to us?
For several years, the online journal "Edge" has published contributions from renowned scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far, where we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we should at least hope, as all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to another species and slash questions of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter immovable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it sets itself up dead, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude to a similar subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to convey our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits almost always associated with the human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This wide region is much higher developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely missing in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to assume that man is different even from the other primates.
