Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Associate in California Studies and Senior Director in Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing Spanish voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign notes that “the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully graduating from school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition in education for those who first learn English.
Nevertheless, Obama’s question is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take, for example, “Sixth Street Prep”, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom are recently in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, astonishing 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state exam in mathematics at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated good in the English exam.
This astonishing success has been achieved by methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The School Sixth Street focuses on review and exercise, on constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is practicing the approach according to which the training is carried out in an English-speaking environment, which is precisely the point that Obama should pay attention to, says school principal Linda Mikel.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in the field of instruction.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school would have had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later you would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize it anymore.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the “Sixth Street Prep” as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English learners?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation aimed at "English only."
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work, rather than disdaining and trivializing them.
