Understanding - From the Blood that Became Safe Again
Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be delighted, as Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public trust, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross donation service were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and to elaborate guidelines on this type of cataclysm.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the management of blood preservatives in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to provide for the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preservatives and by working in this field over the next few years, we have regained public trust,” she says, before emphasizing proudly that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that ‘trust is something extremely fragile’.
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine intelligence in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we are referring to one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which one applies exclusion measures if one is not aware of this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which leads to a degeneration of the brain.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was undoubtedly proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the precautionary principle that we applied is quite meaningful.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the Nucleic Acid Tests (NSTs), which allow directly in the blood of the donor to prove the presence of the virus itself, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million blood preservatives before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preservatives each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV to be transmitted via a blood preservative.
I believe that you can feel comfortable doing it these days when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore your health,” says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can enter the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to constantly monitor," said Dr. Décary, stressing that Hema-Québec must also provide adequate supply in addition to a safe supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
As treatments for cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, only 3% of Quebec’s people are eligible for blood donation.
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they are ill with, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who travel to a country where malaria is widespread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
With this 3%, we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you need to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It’s hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all, to keep them and make them become regular donors.
“Life is so hectic nowadays that you rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of <0x24>297 million, Hema-Québec delivers not only blood preservatives but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyelids and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being interposed at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec.
In the navel cord, which was previously considered a biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth navel cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand annually.
“We should probably start by the beginning of next year by making it available for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program as very popular.
‘Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it’, as Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
