The Psychology of Overwhelmingness – Or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In the event of increases, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the wrong bidder.
Neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological and economic fundamentals of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to be beaten in a competition, such as an increase on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play the lottery while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the spine, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which overcoming the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally employed research to track money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their efforts.
Another group was also promised a <0x24>15 reward in case they emerged as the winner of the game.
The third group received <0x24>15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neuroscientists, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to wager higher than those in the control or "gain" group.
“These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviors observed in auctions have so far been justified only with the pleasure of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved thanks to imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to visit the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, due to the fact that patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the causes and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on the cause, hepatitis viruses spread to two different types: in the case of hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, semen or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B anyway, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and fracture.
After that, yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-caused, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people are infected with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the trigger destroys the liver cells at home - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients is estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the pharmacist for the first signs of unknown origin.
Timely recognized, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banning the risk of infection and preventing the onset of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, the first time in 2004 hosted by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic liver inflammations caused by viruses, their formation and the importance of early detection.
