What would be the best method to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to mimic the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummeln to create new accident-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the auto-robot-driven biomimetic system of type BR23C, a mini-car, equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, Product Manager for Technology PR and Research Development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bees, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers came up with the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately initiates the collision-preventing process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the autobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by rotating the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If not, the autobot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the “Mobility Laboratory” and the autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer, within the accidents still considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a fraction of a second.
However, the evasion, unlike the bees, can not take place upwards, downwards, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and that is only in the direction of the rotation of the tyres.
While there are infinite possibilities for the bees to escape from other bees, the researchers were able to use the autobot only the motion of rotation, acceleration and slowdown.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of data, and less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It does not have to save them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous maneuvers, so it constantly takes only a handful of KB memory.
It does not require gigabytes and megabytes of hard memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision-prevention technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production in series over the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously driving the driver around obstacles and leading him to his destination.
