When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up.
It is a non-successful source of money that covers over 70% of the planet’s surface, and it is only now that the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been under consideration and researched for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have increased significantly since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke in 1980, the idea of marine energy was distorted, but now environmental organisations and the rise in oil prices are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This is equivalent to double the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
There are also the currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the opportunity to work with us.”
This is about acquiring an approval from the U.S. Energy Commission necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially considering that it is in Alaska that oil is still being promoted by the United States and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the New York-based companies Debt Power Inc. and Ocean Power, New Jersey, are also investing in the new industry; the details are not known, however, observers say.
Nonetheless, there are technologies that can be improved.
Experts speak of a technology that is still on the rise, not least because the last doubts of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are quite small and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different ways: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected bows.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the bows up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the float via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are still pending state approval, and some of the energy generated could also be used for military facilities.
Debt Power, however, already produces energy for a warehouse and a parking lot using undersea turbines in New York’s East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential customers is already awaiting the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electrical Research, there is a particular interest in the potential that lies in the tides.
While this is also an irregular phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind currents, sunlight and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
